    <text>
        <body>
            <head>205. Paper Prepared in the <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">National Security
                    Council</orgName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d205fn1">Source: Reagan Library,
                        <persName corresp="rech6OQ6N5EdBVhDo">Carlucci</persName> Files, <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The President</persName>
                    (09/10/1987–10/31/1987). Top Secret; Sensitive. <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName> wrote in the upper left-hand
                    corner: “OK <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">RR</persName>.”</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1987-09-10"
                        >September 10, 1987</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <p>[Omitted here is material related to <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss>, <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15">nuclear
                    testing</rs>, <rs corresp="rectadvRz4QZmc1z7" type="topic">chemical
                weapons</rs>, and <rs type="topic" corresp="recQl77x6qBlGdnAY">conventional
                    arms</rs>]</p>
            <p rendition="simple_centre">
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs corresp="recQ5xJqddmHqhjNl" type="topic">ARMS CONTROL</rs> DECISIONS</hi>
            </p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p>a. <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID">Mobiles</rs>
                </hi>. The US will consider permitting mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> in a <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement at/near end-game on the negotiations if needed to conclude an
                agreement that is otherwise in our interests and provided that the Soviets are
                prepared to work with us in good faith to agree on acceptable associated <rs
                    corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic">verification</rs> measures.</p>
            <pb facs="0924" n="897" xml:id="pg_897"/>
            <p>While the US should not signal flexibility on <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recInQ6JTYKBeryID">mobiles</rs> to the Soviet Union at this time, an
                internal assessment should be done to determine the best possible approaches for
                verifying limits on road and rail mobile <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>.</p>
            <p>b. <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">Sub-limits</rs>
                </hi>. The US will be prepared to respond to Soviet flexibility in <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> by showing some flexibility on sub-limits. There should be no flexibility
                shown on:</p>
            <quote>
                <p>6000 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs> &amp;
                        <gloss target="#t_ALCM_1">
                        <rs corresp="rec3r8I0hO6jAW3Fm" type="topic">ALCMs</rs>
                    </gloss> (+ compensation for bomber weapons under the <rs type="event"
                        corresp="recY5TBKXKBIuAnWc">Reykjavik</rs>
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recYq8ReZQ3bXtQu4">bomber counting rule</rs>.)</p>
                <p>1600 total <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>
                    and <rs type="topic" corresp="rectLhSs11Y4ZQ6zE">heavy bombers</rs>
                </p>
                <p>4800 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on <rs
                        type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>
                </p>
                <p>1540 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on heavy <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">
                        <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                    </gloss>
                </p>
            </quote>
            <p>In showing flexibility, the initial move should be the relaxing of our current
                proposal of a sub-limit of 3300 on total <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss> to 3600 <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> on
                    <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="reccap2GMokKh4v4P" type="topic">ICBMs</rs>
                </gloss>. (This <rs type="topic" corresp="recNg1LuXkmZCFR19">sublimit</rs> should
                not be extended to apply to <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                    >warheads</rs> on <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recnGcR0g6J7yKHTE" type="topic">SLBMs</rs>
                </gloss> as well).</p>
            <p>c. <hi rendition="simple_italic">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </hi>. The best the US can do in this area is to offer to make unilateral statements
                about the existing and planned nuclear <gloss target="#t_SLCM_1">
                    <rs corresp="recRMohN3AY0ch5I7" type="topic">SLCM</rs>
                </gloss> forces of both sides.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">DEFENSE &amp; SPACE</rs>
            </p>
            <p>a. <hi rendition="simple_italic">Bottom Line</hi>. Protect the promise of <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> at all costs. Regardless of whether the US forswears its pursuit of active
                    <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defenses</rs> against
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recr08QgEMEm1Bk04">ballistic missiles</rs>, none doubt
                that the Soviets are now and will continue to dig the massive, deep shelters that
                they are permitted to build under the terms of the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1"
                    >ABM</gloss>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recKv8RyteDQ8sLn9">Treaty</rs>. The Soviet
                Union will defend those things it values most. The issue for the future is whether
                the US will be permitted to protect what it values. A future effective <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> deployment program (not merely the existence of an <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recJclekZAp3yKmD5">research</rs> program) is the basis for
                a more secure future for the US and her <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recydYSQ1GmGAh8yu">Allies</rs>.</p>
            <p>b. <hi rendition="simple_italic">No Framework Agreements</hi>. We should avoid any
                “framework agreements” that cover the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> and <rs type="event" corresp="rec0rc9kDG6TIF88N">Defense and Space</rs>
                area since they will effectively put in place anticipated restrictions on <gloss
                    target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> on us while not being sufficient to allow us to see <gloss
                    target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k">reductions</rs> begin.</p>
            <p>c. <hi rendition="simple_italic">6 Month Notification Prior to Deployment</hi>. As
                needed, we can add to our current position a provision calling for a “6 month
                notification of either side’s intent to deploy <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defenses</rs> not currently permitted” after 1
                January 1995 when each side can choose to deploy such <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recKKNyP9NHSwF6fs">defenses</rs>.</p>
            <p>[Omitted here is material related to <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss>, <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15">nuclear
                    testing</rs>, <rs corresp="rectadvRz4QZmc1z7" type="topic">chemical
                weapons</rs>, and <rs type="topic" corresp="recQl77x6qBlGdnAY">conventional</rs>
                arms.]</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <gloss target="#t_INF_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recgLCwFE47waxYP9">INF</rs>
                </gloss>
            </p>
            <p>a. <hi rendition="simple_italic">Overall</hi>. The <rs type="agreement-or-mandate"
                    corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">
                    <gloss target="#t_INF_1">INF</gloss> Treaty</rs> is a major accomplishment. We
                should resolve the remaining “minor” issues as quickly as possible so that we can
                get this <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">Treaty</rs>
                ratified and implemented while you are still in office.</p>
            <pb facs="0925" n="898" xml:id="pg_898"/>
            <p>b. <hi rendition="simple_italic">Status</hi>. We have resolved most of the critical
                issues associated with this <rs type="agreement-or-mandate"
                    corresp="reclckIw9AgH05Yxw">Treaty</rs>. While a lot of details still need to be
                ironed out (e.g., the schedule of <rs type="topic" corresp="recHoFOsQcM4e5M4k"
                    >reductions</rs>, details of <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >verification</rs>, status of flight testing, etc.), the only remaining major
                issue between the US and Soviet Union has to do with the US <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs> provided under an existing program of
                cooperation with the <placeName corresp="recUe17pTh04JBoo9">Federal Republic of
                    Germany</placeName> for their Pershing IA missiles.</p>
            <p>c. <hi rendition="simple_italic">US <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga"
                        >Warheads</rs> for <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recwGjqxOysaY22y9"
                        >German</rs> Pershing IA Missiles</hi>. We cannot undercut the basic
                principle that such existing programs of cooperation are not subject to bilateral
                negotiation. Provided that the Soviet Union can be satisfied by the statement made
                by Chancellor <persName corresp="recUBq6g7UnnFrRVV">Kohl</persName> that the <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recwGjqxOysaY22y9">German</rs> PIAs will be
                eliminated, and the subsequent statements by US spokesmen that in such a
                circumstance, the US <rs type="topic" corresp="recfkRWjb8Vcm4Gga">warheads</rs>
                would be withdrawn, we should be able to conclude a Treaty in this area this fall.
                This being the case, we should do what we can to conclude this treaty.</p>
            <p>d. <hi rendition="simple_italic">Reduction Schedule</hi>. We wanted to eliminate the
                missiles involved as quickly as possible. The current plan, proposed by the <gloss
                    target="#t_JCS_1">
                    <orgName corresp="recYt5V8hImTp3Aah">JCS</orgName>
                </gloss> and agreed by all agencies, would have the missiles destroyed within <hi
                    rendition="simple_italic">3 years</hi>. We are about to discuss the details with
                our <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recydYSQ1GmGAh8yu">allies</rs>.</p>
            <p>e. <hi rendition="simple_italic">New <rs type="topic" corresp="recYKTo2QC0yLpT7N"
                        >Draft Treaty</rs>
                </hi>. We hope to be in a position to table a new treaty by next Monday.<note n="2"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d205fn2">September 14.</note> To do so, needed to make the
                following decisions:</p>
            <p>1. To clarify that this treaty <hi rendition="simple_italic">only</hi> covers <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="rec43jYPGDcX0aJRW">SRINF</rs>/<gloss target="#t_LRINF_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="reczU3lVS4eZr8vxf">LRINF</rs>
                </gloss> missiles designed to attack targets on the surface of the earth (and not
                    <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_ASAT_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recK25AUjO3toNZWX">ASAT</rs>
                </gloss> or <rs type="topic" corresp="recY4zdE5fZQUvoyu">air defense</rs> missiles
                that could fly to similar ranges).</p>
            <p>2. No flight testing after treaty is signed. This would include using the launching
                of these missiles (e.g., US <rs type="topic" corresp="recj3V5JyPN7ZoaIK"
                    >Pershings</rs>) to “destroy” them. Therefore, we can’t use <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recj3V5JyPN7ZoaIK">Pershings</rs> for other testing, spacelaunch
                vehicles, or as targets for <gloss target="#t_SDI_1">
                    <rs type="program" corresp="recVUMTljdyxyuZz3">SDI</rs>
                </gloss> experiments.</p>
            <p>3. Permit <rs type="topic" corresp="recJclekZAp3yKmD5">research and development</rs>
                missiles for other purposes as long as they</p>
            <quote>
                <p>(1) are not existing types of <rs type="topic" corresp="rec43jYPGDcX0aJRW"
                        >SRINF</rs>/<gloss target="#t_LRINF_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="reczU3lVS4eZr8vxf">LRINF</rs>
                    </gloss> missiles;</p>
                <p>(2) are limited in number; and</p>
                <p>(3) are not used to develop new <rs type="topic" corresp="rec43jYPGDcX0aJRW"
                        >SRINF</rs>/<gloss target="#t_LRINF_1">
                        <rs type="topic" corresp="reczU3lVS4eZr8vxf">LRINF</rs>
                    </gloss> missiles.</p>
            </quote>
            <p>4. Ban all armed <rs type="topic" corresp="recEYJpmEGRfvJpPc">ground launched cruise
                    missiles</rs> (including those which are conventionally armed) beyond 500
                kilometers. This is needed for <rs corresp="recvMEtDFpnXkyj45" type="topic"
                    >verification</rs>, but it does foreclose future US/<gloss target="#t_NATO_1">
                    <orgName corresp="rec9wzMIGHUgT4FsE">NATO</orgName>
                </gloss> options for advanced conventionally armed <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recqaxqBsfTYVWHfR">cruise missiles</rs> at these longer ranges. (SecDef
                objects strongly to this decision and it may cause complaint from some
                conservatives.)</p>
        </body>
    </text>
